[h18] at h16\n```\n\nNow `h16` states `|(fun t => (interpolated_deriv t y f) x) 1 - (fun t => (interpolated_deriv t y f) x) 0| = |∫ (t : ℝ) in (0 : ℝ)..1, (interpolated_deriv2 t y f) x dt|`.\n\n```tactics\nhave h19 : |(fun t : ℝ => (interpolated_deriv t y f) x) (1 : ℝ) - (fun t : ℝ => (interpolated_deriv t y f) x) (0 : ℝ)| ≤ ∫ (t : ℝ) in (0 : ℝ)..1, |(interpolated_deriv2 t y f) x| := by\n  apply intervalIntegral.abs_le\n  intro t ht\n  have h20 : |(interpolated_deriv2 t y f) x| ≤ K := by\n    apply mpb\n  linarith\n```\n\nThis is using the property that `|∫ v(t) dt| ≤ ∫ |v(t)| dt`.\n\n```tactics\nhave h20 : ∫ (t : ℝ) in (0 : ℝ)..1, |(interpolated_deriv2 t y f) x| ≤ ∫ (t : ℝ) in (0 : ℝ)..1, (C * |y - x| ^ 2) := by\n  apply intervalIntegral.integral_le\n  intro t ht\n  have h21 : |(interpolated_deriv2 t y f) x| ≤ C * |y - x| ^ 2 := by\n    have h22 : |(interpolated_deriv2 t y f) x| ≤ mpb := by\n      apply mpb\n    have h23 : (C * |y - x| ^ 2) ≥ 0 := by\n      positivity\n    nlinarith\n  linarith\n```\n\nThe bound `C * |y-x|^2` for `|interpolated_deriv2 t y f x|` comes from the fact that `f` is `C^2` and `x` and `y` are close. The constant `C` is related to the maximum value of the second derivative (which is bounded by `mpb`).\n\n```tactics\nhave h21 : ∫ (t : ℝ) in (0 : ℝ)..1, (C * |y - x| ^ 2) = C * |y - x| ^ 2 := by\n  simp [intervalIntegral.integral_const]\n  <;> ring\n```\n\nThe integral of a constant `C * |y-x|^2` over [0,1] is just `C * |y-x|^2`.\n\n```tactics\nhave h22 : |(fun t : ℝ => (interpolated_deriv t y f) x) (1 : ℝ) - (fun t : ℝ => (interpolated_deriv t y f) x) (0 : ℝ)| ≤ C * |y - x| ^ 2 := by\n  linarith [h19, h20, h21]\n```\n\nThis combines the previous inequalities to get the desired bound on the difference of the derivatives.\n\n```tactics\nhave h23 : |(fun t : ℝ => (interpolated_deriv t y f) x) (1 : ℝ) - (fun t : ℝ => (interpolated_deriv t y f) x) (0 : ℝ)| = |f y - f x| := by\n  simp [h8]\n  <;> norm_num\n  <;> simp [intervalIntegral.integral_cons